couting and Guiding in Colombia|Colombia]]\n| Asociaci\u00f3n Colombiana de Escultismo (ACE)\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in the Dutch Caribbean|Cura\u00e7ao]]\n| Independent Scouts of Cura\u00e7ao\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Ecuador|Ecuador]]\n| Asociaci\u00f3n de Boy Scouts del Ecuador\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in El Salvador|El Salvador]]\n| Asociacion de Scouts Independientes de El Salvador ASI-ES\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Guatemala|Guatemala]]\n| Asociaci\u00f3n de Escultismo Ecol\u00f3gico Baden-Powell Guatemala\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Honduras|Honduras]]\n| Asociaci\u00f3n Hondure\u00f1a de Escultismo Tradicional\n| full member\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | [[Scouting and Guiding in Mexico|Mexico]]\n| [[:es:AGSMEX|Agrupaci\u00f3n Scout Mexicana, A.C.]]\n| full member\n|-\n| Asociaci\u00f3n Nacional de Scouts Independientes Mexico (ANSI)\n| full member\n|-\n| Federaci\u00f3n Mexicana de Scouts Independientes, A.C.\n| full member\n|-\n| Asociaci\u00f3n Tradicionalista de Scouts Tiro y Pesca, A.C.\n| full member\n|-\n| Asociaci\u00f3n de Scouts del Sureste A.C.\n| prospect member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Panama|Panama]]\n| Cuerpo de Exploradores Paname\u00f1os\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Paraguay|Paraguay]]\n| Hermandad Scout de Paraguay\n| full member\n|-\n| [[Scouting in the United States|United States]]\n| [[Baden-Powell Service Association]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Baden-Powell Service Association, US |url=http://www.bpsa-us.org/ |accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref>\n|  full member\n|}\n\n===WFIS South-East Asia===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Group\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]]\n| Independent Scouts of Bangladesh\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in mainland China|China]]\n| Shanghai Scout Association\n|-\n| [[Scouting in Korea|South Korea]]\n| Third Eye Scouting Association\n|-\n|rowspan=3| [[Scouting and Guiding in Pakistan|Pakistan]]\n| Independent Scouts of Pakistan\n|-\n| Nankana Sab Scout Organization\n|-\n| ADABKADA Scout Association\n|-\n| [[Scouting and Guiding in Sri Lanka|Sri Lanka]]\n| Independent Scouts of Sri Lanka\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[Scouting and Guiding in the United Arab Emirates|United Arab Emirates]]\n| United Arab Emirates Independent Scout Association\n|-\n| Dubai Scout Organization\n|}\n\n==Jamborees and international camps==\n\n{{Main|World Federation of Independent Scouts World Jamboree}}\n\nWFIS has held World Jamborees in 2002, 2007, and 2011.\n\nIn addition to World Jamborees, the WFIS also regularly host regional international camps, such as Eurocamp. The following camps having taken place or are scheduled:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Event !! Location, Country !! Theme !! Dates\n|-\n| 2006 || Eurocamp 2006 || [[Switzerland]] || ||\n|-\n| 2010 || Eurocamp 2010 || [[Germany]] || ||\n|-\n| 2014 || Eurocamp 2014 || [[Italy]] || ||\n|-\n| 2018 || [http://eurocamp18.com/ Eurocamp 2018] || [[Newbury, Berkshire]], [[United Kingdom]] || Lifelong friendships created by Scouting || 28 July to 4 August 2018\n|}\n\nWFIS also hosts a Jamboree On The Internet:\n* WFIS-JOTI 2010, hosted by WFIS Africa<ref>http://joti.wfis-africa.org/ WFIS-JOTI 2010</ref>\n\nMember Associations also regularly invite each other to their own camps, examples including:\n* [[Jamboree 2008 (Northumberland)]]\n* The Baden-Powell Scouts' Association 2007 Centenary Camp\n\n==International Scout Fellowship==\n{{Infobox WorldScouting\n| type = Organization\n| name = International Scout Fellowship\n| image = International Scout Fellowship.svg\n| imagesize = 90px\n| caption =\n| headquarters =\n| location =\n| country = Worldwide\n| f-date = 2007-08-01\n| founder =\n| award-for =\n| members =\n| website ={{URL|https://isf-world.org/}}\n}}\nThe International Scout Fellowship is an affiliate of WFIS, but not a member.\nIt is open to former and current adult members of WFIS, to other adult friends of Independent Scouting who wish to contribute to independent Scouting, regardless of their Scouting backgrounds.\n\nThe ISF is governed by its World Council which is composed of representatives of each member Chapter.  It meets once a year, usually electronically.  Its day-to-day affairs are directed by the Executive Committee, which is elected by the World Council.\n\nAll positions in the ISF are staffed by volunteers.  There are no paid employees.\n\n===Uniform===\nThe badge is that of the WFIS in reverse colours.\nThere is no set uniform of the ISF.  Member chapters determine their own uniforms with the badge of the ISF. Other chapters may use casual dress such as T-shirts, etc.\n\nThe emphasis of the ISF is on tangible results in supporting Independent Scouting associations, not on formalities.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Portal:Scouting | The Scouting Portal ]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wfis-worldwide.org/start.html WFIS Worldwide]\n{{-}}\n{{scouting|international}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Federation Of Independent Scouts}}\n[[Category:International Scouting organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-aligned Scouting organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1996]]\n", "name_user": "Lkmorlan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJamborees and international camps:Put other jamborees in chronological order", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Federation_of_Independent_Scouts"}
{"title_page": "Tzur Hadassah", "text_new": "{{Infobox Kibbutz\n| name = Tzur Hadassah\n| hebname = \u05e6\u05d5\u05bc\u05e8 \u05d4\u05b2\u05d3\u05b7\u05e1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4\n| image = TzurHadassah.JPG\n| foundation = 1960\n| founded_by = \n| district = jerusalem\n| council = [[Mateh Yehuda Regional Council|Mateh Yehuda]]\n| affiliation =\n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Zur Hadassa}}\n| population_footnotes={{Israel populations|reference}}\n| pushpin_map=Israel jerusalem |pushpin_mapsize=250\n|coordinates = {{coord|31|43|9.17|N|35|5|51.46|E|display=inline,title}}\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Tzur Hadassah''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05d5\u05bc\u05e8 \u05d4\u05b2\u05d3\u05b7\u05e1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}, ''lit.'' Rock of Hadassah) is a town located in the [[Jerusalem Corridor]], located {{convert|12|km|mi}} southwest of Jerusalem, at an altitude of 755 meters above sea level, located on Route 375 west of [[Betar Ilit]], about one kilometer west of the [[Green Line (Israel)|Green Line]]. According to the [[Central Bureau of Statistics (Israel)|Central Bureau of Statistics]], Tzur Hadassah is the largest settlement in Israel that does not have a local authority status. It falls under the jurisdiction of [[Mateh Yehuda Regional Council]]. In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Zur Hadassa}}.{{Israel populations|reference}} In 2016, plans for expansion were approved, which would add 15,000 new residents within 5 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yediot.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4791224,00.html|title=\u05d0\u05d5\u05db\u05dc\u05d5\u05e1\u05d9\u05d9\u05ea \u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05d3\u05e1\u05d4 \u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05e4\u05dc \u05d1\u05be5 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05ea \u05e9\u05db\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4|date=2016-04-14|website=ynet|language=he|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nTzur Hadassah was established in 1956 as a regional centre for nearby [[moshav]]im such as ([[Bar Giora (moshav)|Bar Giora]], [[Mata(moshav)|Mata]], [[Mevo Beitar]] and [[Nes Harim]]) on land that had belonged to the depopulated [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] village of [[Ras Abu 'Ammar]].<ref>{{cite book|title=All That Remains: The Palestinian Villages Occupied and Depopulated by Israel in 1948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_By7AAAAIAAJ |first=Walid|last=Khalidi|authorlink=Walid Khalidi|year=1992|location=[[Washington D.C.]]|publisher=[[Institute for Palestine Studies]]|isbn=0-88728-224-5|page=312}}</ref> It was named for the [[Hadassah]] organization.\n\nThe town has four neighborhoods: Old Tzur Hadassah (Shehunat HaMeah); New Tzur Hadassah (Shehunat HaEmek); Har Sansan (Sansan Mt.); And Har Kitron (Kitron Mt.) which forms the second half of the [[horseshoe]] [[topography]] of Tzur Hadassah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbn.org.il/aliyahpedia-home/community-housing/|title=Communities & Housing in Israel}}</ref>\n\nThe Harei Yehuda riding stable is located in Tzur Hadassah, at the edge of the Sansan nature reserve. It  was established in 1991 in the old part of Tzur Hadassah and moved to new facilities in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hyr.co.il/en/|title=Harei Yehuda - Stable Tsur Hadassah|website=www.hyr.co.il}}</ref> The [[Israel National Trail]], marked with orange, blue, and white stripes, reaches Tzur Hadassah on its way westward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eretz.com/NEW/trailela.shtml|title=ERETZ Magazine|website=www.eretz.com}}</ref> In 2014, construction workers discovered a large stalactite cave near Tzur Hadassah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishpress.com/news/breaking-news/huge-stalactite-cave-discovered-near-gush-etzion/2014/09/21/|title=Huge Stalactite Cave Discovered Near Gush Etzion|first=Tzvi|last=Ben-Gedalyahu}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ras Abu 'Ammar]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Tzur Hadassa as seen from Khiebet Jurish.jpg|Tzur Hadassah as seen from Khirbet Jurish\nFile:Tzur Hadassa as seen from Kh. Jurish.jpg|Tzur Hadassa (from Kh. Jurish)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tzur-hadassa.org.il/ Official website] {{in lang|he}}\n\n{{Mateh Yehuda Regional Council}}\n\n[[Category:Community settlements]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Jerusalem District]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Kibbutz\n| name = Tzur Hadassah\n| hebname = \u05e6\u05d5\u05bc\u05e8 \u05d4\u05b2\u05d3\u05b7\u05e1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4\n| image = TzurHadassah.JPG\n| foundation = 1960\n| founded_by = \n| district = jerusalem\n| council = [[Mateh Yehuda Regional Council|Mateh Yehuda]]\n| affiliation =\n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Zur Hadassa}}\n| population_footnotes={{Israel populations|reference}}\n| pushpin_map=Israel jerusalem |pushpin_mapsize=250\n|coordinates = {{coord|31|43|9.17|N|35|5|51.46|E|display=inline,title}}\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Tzur Hadassah''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05d5\u05bc\u05e8 \u05d4\u05b2\u05d3\u05b7\u05e1\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4}}, ''lit.'' Rock of Hadassah) is a town located in the [[Jerusalem Corridor]], located {{convert|12|km|mi}} southwest of Jerusalem, at an altitude of 755 meters above sea level, located on Route 375 west of [[Betar Ilit]], about one kilometer west of the [[Green Line (Israel)|Green Line]]. According to the [[Central Bureau of Statistics (Israel)|Central Bureau of Statistics]], Tzur Hadassah is the largest settlement in Israel that does not have a local authority status. It falls under the jurisdiction of [[Mateh Yehuda Regional Council]]. In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Zur Hadassa}}.{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==History==\nTzur Hadassah was established in 1956 as a regional centre for nearby [[moshav]]im such as ([[Bar Giora (moshav)|Bar Giora]], [[Mata(moshav)|Mata]], [[Mevo Beitar]] and [[Nes Harim]]) on land that had belonged to the depopulated [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] village of [[Ras Abu 'Ammar]].<ref>{{cite book|title=All That Remains: The Palestinian Villages Occupied and Depopulated by Israel in 1948|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_By7AAAAIAAJ |first=Walid|last=Khalidi|authorlink=Walid Khalidi|year=1992|location=[[Washington D.C.]]|publisher=[[Institute for Palestine Studies]]|isbn=0-88728-224-5|page=312}}</ref> It was named for the [[Hadassah]] organization.\n\nThe town has four neighborhoods: Old Tzur Hadassah (Shehunat HaMeah); New Tzur Hadassah (Shehunat HaEmek); Har Sansan (Sansan Mt.); And Har Kitron (Kitron Mt.) which forms the second half of the [[horseshoe]] [[topography]] of Tzur Hadassah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbn.org.il/aliyahpedia-home/community-housing/|title=Communities & Housing in Israel}}</ref>\n\nThe Harei Yehuda riding stable is located in Tzur Hadassah, at the edge of the Sansan nature reserve. It  was established in 1991 in the old part of Tzur Hadassah and moved to new facilities in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hyr.co.il/en/|title=Harei Yehuda - Stable Tsur Hadassah|website=www.hyr.co.il}}</ref> The [[Israel National Trail]], marked with orange, blue, and white stripes, reaches Tzur Hadassah on its way westward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eretz.com/NEW/trailela.shtml|title=ERETZ Magazine|website=www.eretz.com}}</ref> In 2014, construction workers discovered a large stalactite cave near Tzur Hadassah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishpress.com/news/breaking-news/huge-stalactite-cave-discovered-near-gush-etzion/2014/09/21/|title=Huge Stalactite Cave Discovered Near Gush Etzion|first=Tzvi|last=Ben-Gedalyahu}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ras Abu 'Ammar]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Tzur Hadassa as seen from Khiebet Jurish.jpg|Tzur Hadassah as seen from Khirbet Jurish\nFile:Tzur Hadassa as seen from Kh. Jurish.jpg|Tzur Hadassa (from Kh. Jurish)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links=